title: For Sale/Trade:  .308 AK! Zastava M77 custom
postcontent: Selling my Zastava M77 in .308. It has never been fired except for test firing at factory. I reconfigured it from the factory "Sporter" with (ugly) plastic furniture to the military configuration with wood furniture. I rebuilt the rear of the receiver which is cut at an angle from the factory for the plastic thumbhole stock. This required a new rear trunnion from an M70 type AK, and welding in a new piece to the sheet metal receiver to restore the angled cut to square. This forms the correct socket for the wood stock.I used a new US made walnut stock set, not a surplus stock set.  Also included: Tapco G2 trigger, upgraded hammer and trigger pin plate (improvement over the stock wire type), Limbsaver butt pad, CNC Warrior flash hider/muzzle brake, Vickers sling, RS AK-307 modular side mount and scope rails.  I'm not including a scope with it but it does have the mounts and I can add a set of Burris tactical 30mm rings. All together I have about $1500 in this rifle (NOT including a scope). I am including the original 10 round magazine, and two CO legal 15 round (pinned 20 round) magazines made for the Zastava M77 from CSSpecs. Firm on the price considering the extensive upgrades and it's never been fired. 922r compliant with all the US-made components.Buyer pays background check at FFL of your choice. There are a couple I know of that will do third party transfers. Denver metro only please.

title: For Sale:  John Inglis- Browing Hi Power
postcontent: Browning Hi-power manufactured by the John Inglis Co. in Canada.  Only in production for 1 year between 1944-1945.  Comes with three Mags and original lanyard.History:High-Power pistols were also produced in Canada for Allied use, by JohnInglis & Co. in Toronto. The plans were sent from the FN factory to Britain when it became clear the Belgian plant would fall into German hands, enabling the Inglis factory to be tooled up for Hi-Power production for Allied use. Inglis produced two versions of the Hi-Power, one with an adjustable rear sight and detachable shoulder stock (primarily for a Nationalist Chinese contract) and one with a fixed rear sight. Production began in late 1944 and they were on issue by the March 1945 Operation Varsity airborne crossing of the Rhine into Germany. The pistol was popular with the British airborne forces as well as covert operations and commando groups such as the Special Operations Executive (SOE), the U.S. Office of Strategic Services (OSS) and the British Special Air Services (SAS) Regiment. Inglis High-Powers made for Commonwealth forces have the British designation 'Mk 1', or 'Mk 1*' and the manufacturer's details on the left of the slide. They were known in British and Commonwealth service as the 'Pistol No 2 Mk 1', or 'Pistol No 2 Mk 1*' where applicable. Serial numbers were 6 characters, the second being the letter 'T', e.g. 1T2345. Serial numbers on pistols for the Chinese contract instead used the letters 'CH', but otherwise followed the same format. When the Chinese contract was cancelled, all undelivered Chinese-style pistols were accepted by the Canadian military with designations of 'Pistol No 1 Mk 1' and 'Pistol No 1 Mk 1*'.
